100% pure race dogs are that expensive. But otherwise, if people are less 
picky about pedigrees and stuff, you can get all of these "expensive" races 
for a much lower price. For example, dogs in animal refuges are extremly 
cheap, sometime you can get amazing dogs there, or even little cute puppies 
(+ the good feeling of having saved an animal from a sure death).

I don't want to discredit dogs factories...aka "breeders" (specially since 
my aunt breeding airedale dogs), but sometime the dogs they produced are 
mentaly fucktop or physicaly sick (visit them more than once, check if they 
have their certifications, don't be shy to ask questions, and don't be too 
hasty). It's always better to take your time and evaluate how they take 
care of their dogs and how trustable they are (you absolutly don't want to 
buy a pricy sick dogs!!).

If you really want to buy a pure breed dog, double-triple check his/her 
pedigree to not encourage un-credited breeders (i already bought a cat who 
was suposed to be a pure race, while she was'nt... but i still love her)... 
specially if you plan to do breeding one day ... or do dog beauty 
competitions (they are use to ask for tons of certificates).  Also, pure 
breed dogs are use to have specific genetic deseases due to their 
consanguinity or their abnormal specific proportions (example: pure blue 
danish dogs have severe heart problems due to their abnormal size, bulldogs 
have problems to give birth due to their abnormal small hips, some other 
races have major eyes problems due to an abnormal hair abundance, some dog 
breeds have specific temper too etc). Sometime mix races are a better and 
more conveniant choices (like labrador/german shepherd, 
pomeranian/chihuahua etc)... + it could solve some of these genetic/racial 
problems. 

You'll have to deal with your dog for many many years, so think twice 
before doing any move, because it'll have an impact in your life and 
his/her's. Think twice and evaluate your needs (to protect your house, to 
hunt with, or as zootherapy etc), your situation (kids or not, living in a 
city or on the countryside etc), the time you could give them (like if you 
work full time and only have little time to give him/her) and the dog's 
specific needs (outdoor dogs aren't ment for small city appartments... 
instead if you plan to go in a park real REAL frequently). 

To have a dog represent a lot of responsabilities, to get a pure breed dog 
represent even more responsabilities. There's too many good and amazing 
dogs who are daily left in dog refuges... be more carefull please.﻿
